{"/service/ndnp/nvln/batch_nvln_idlewild_ver01/data/sn86076241/00271762318/1914030401/0200.xml":{"full_text":"CARSON CITY DAILY APPEAL WEDNESDAY. MARCH 4, lfl4\nThe Carson City Daily fffrpeal\nCARSON CITY, ORMSHY COUNTY, NEVADA\nKntered as Matter of the Second Class at the I'ostoffice at Carson\nCity, Nevada, under Act of Congress of March 3, 1879\nPUBLISHED EVEKY EVENING, EXCEPT SUNDAY, BY THE\nNEVADA PRINTING COMPANY\nT. D. Van Devort, Editor. H. J. Coogan, Manager\nTERMS OF SUBSCRIPTION\nOne Year, in Advance, by Carrier $12.00\nIan Year, in Advance, by Mail 9-00\nOffical Advertising Medium of the State of Nevada and for tl\nCounty of Ormsby, Nevada\nThe Carson City Daily Appeal is the real live advertising medium\nof this section as is evidenced by its carrying a larger\namount of advertising than any paper in the city.\nEDNLSDAY EVENING\nM ARTI 4. P:4\nNEW IDEAS IN GOVERNMENT\nIf the pirns \"t the el'tu-luK'y engineers appointed by the\nlegislature M'c carried tit the k vei ii.,r wilt be made the actual he ul\nof every 'iii-in I the executive department ..f the -tate govern\nment. In addition to this reform, it i pr iposed that all -tate judges\nshall be api)ointed by tin- Jiict justice of the -tate Supreme court.\nThis em, if dopted. will have the advantage of bringing the\ngovernor direitly i;i t.'i.ch with the work of every department of the\ngovernment, and while it will inerca-e hi- labor and power it will cen\ntralis authority ami shotdd lead to greater efficiency. It will make\nit an easy matter for the people and legislature to hx re-onsibility lor\nerrors.\nTlu: proposed m-thod of -electing judges is certainly novel. It\nwill serve to remove the judiciary farther from the field of politics\nthan is possible under the system in u-e in most other state-.\nThe chief justice of the Supreme court would be les- likely to\nfeel political influence than any other official in the -tate, and the\nremoval of the judiciary from the direct mlhtcncc of poli.ic- would\nbe'likcly to give to the judges an added dignity that they cannot hope\nto have under the prc-ctit method ol direct election.\nIowa was an important factor in iiian-:ur.itiug ilu cotnnii.--io.i\nform of government for cities. I'os-ibly it may prove a leader al-o\nin the reform of state government. That the system in vogue i.i mo-t\nof the slates is crude and unsati-lactory i- certain.\nThere seems a disposition in all part- of the country to recon\nstruct the system- of state government and everywhere the tendency\nis to concentration of power in the hand- of few individuals.\nThere is a general recognition of the fact that we do not -ecure\nthe best posible results under the -y-lem. which has remained prac\ntically nr. changed since- the organization ,,f the republic. Sacramento\nUnion.\nTHE BRIGHT BUSINESS OUTLOOK\nNobody any longer doubts that busine-s has turned the corner\nand is steadily improving. Hanker-, merchant- and manufacturer'\nfrom every part of the country who-e views have been published i\nour news columns testify to t!ie nrigtncs- oi the outl ok.\nThe Herald's editorial-, summing up the leading fact- in the -it u\nation and sounding a cheerful bla-t, have roused the de-pondem.\nshamed the calamity howler- and put fresh heart into all who are\nworking to renew and met case the country's prosperity\nThe president yesterday stated that letter- he ha- received show\nthat business generally is good and \"i- unsatisfactory only in a lew\nspots.\"\nIncreased consumption (f copper and steel the ha-ie industries\ngive positive evidence of this improvement. The greater demand\nfor freight cars is al-o evidence that trade is reviving, and further tes\ntimony is offered by the expansion in the country bank clearing- for\nspvcral weeks in succession. It i to be regretted that the interstate\ncommerce coinmi-sion postponed the possible date of it- deci-ion on\nthe application of the railway- to make a 5 per cent advance in freight\nrates. The very fact that they have taken more time for considera\ntion, however,-is evidence that they are not contemplating a refusal of\nthis very reasonable and moderate application. New York Herald.\no(\nNO OFFENSE INTENDED\nThe following communication shows how ea-y it is to give often.-.'\nto people without intending it:\nEditor Appeal: I noticed in a recent is-ue of your paper a poem\nmaking fun of servant girl- It described a servant girl getting\nblown tip by using kero-ene oil to build a lire. I am informed that\nthe slam was intended for me. and. if so. I think a paper has very\nlittle to do slamming a very worthy class of people. I have known\nthe lady of the hoii-e to use kerosene to build lires ami some of the\nbest people do it. 1'lease give this a place in your paper. Respect\nfully. arson housemaid.\nThe Appeal can assure the author ,f the communication that no\nmore spring poetry relative to housniaids kindling lire.- with kerosene\nwill ever appear in these column-. It was not intended for any par\nticular person, but was merely an advertisement of a new brand f\nStandard oil.\nPATRIOTISM OF CITIZENSHIP\nPatriotism is not a mere martial prejudice, a false, beligerent\npride. It is civic, state and national pride to make our municipalities'\nless objectionable to live in, less a home of crime and sordidne-s.\nmore where men and women can work in happiness and children can\nplay in a healthful environment: to make our state the most advanced\nin charity, the quickest to stop abusing the people's rights; to make\nour country the true promised land of the world. How much there\nis to be done!\nThe hardest kind of patriotism is not martial, because it is not ac\ncompanied by fame and glory. It is self-abnegation, considering others\nfirst, helping the weak, encouraging the strong, curbing the unjusr,\nchanging the wicked. Yc cannot all be heroes of peace, wonderful\nexamples to which a nation can point with pride. Hut every one of\nus can do something. Jloston Globe.\n-oo-\nTHE SHERMAN ACT\nThere is a proposition before congress to send the Sherman act to\nthe scrap pile and enact a law in its place that will really curb the\ntrusts.\nThe Sherman act has long since survived its usefulness and was\nnever intended to accompli--, anything any way.\nIt was a sham from the first and unde'r it the trusts thrived won\nderfully well. It was probably fixed up by some trust lavers to fool\nthe very gullible American public and having very thorough servel\nits purpose might as well be shelved now as any time\n(General Carrr.nza, to all appearances wilier than old lluerta him\nself, has put up a proposition to England that has got the diplomats of\nthat nation guessing. Carranza has practically told the American\ngovernment to keep it- nose out of the Benton matter; that it is an\naffair between the Constitutionalists and the British, and a- the latter\nhas recognized the Herta outfit a- the government\nieo it now hardly knows where it is at. It can call\nbut what can he do?\nile facto in Mex\nluerta to account.\nA few months ago. or rather during the session of the last legis\nlature, one \"Bertie\" Mcintosh was wont to remark, \"the press be\ndamned.\" He is now congratulating another person tor probably laud\ning the position he might have had, and to which he would have hail\nlittle opposition, had he been less vehement. The paper- are still go\ning on at the same old stand.\nDRAYING\nMade Every Da\n-oo-\nWiiineumcca has had a big \"get together\" meeting and it is going\nto re-ult in many good things for the benefit of that town and the\ncounty in which it is situated. Carson should follow Winnemucca's\nexample. A movement organized here to do a little boosting and to\nbring opposing elements together would do a lot of material good for\nboth town and county.\noo\nFititeen tons of water must be pumped out in the mines for every\nton uf anthracite coal produced in Pennsylvania.\nLIOHT ANP HEAVY HM'MNU\nOF ALL KINDS\nLWAYS MEET ALL TRAINS\nLeav Ord